Why TrustedInstaller matters:
TrustedInstaller is the service account
that owns Windows system files.

Even Administrators cannot modify
system files without first taking
ownership from TrustedInstaller.

This is why malware that installs
system drivers must either:
  A) Run as TrustedInstaller
     (requires exploit)
  B) Take ownership first
     (leaves forensic evidence)
  C) Use an already-compromised
     TrustedInstaller process
     (what the toolkit does via firmware)

Setting TrustedInstaller as owner
on all system files closes options
A and B at the filesystem layer.
Option C — firmware level — is why
we zero the EFI handles first.
Both layers together.
Run the script from WinRE for cleanest results. After reboot check Event Viewer for any access denied errors — those will be the toolkit trying to access paths it can no longer reach.
