    timestamp     = Get-Date -Format 'o'
    admin_account = $adminName
    admin_sid     = $adminSID
    sandbox_root  = $SANDBOX_ROOT
    paths_sandboxed = $SANDBOX_PATHS.Keys
    watcher_status = $watcherRunning.Status
    original_owner = $acl.Owner
    ti_rights      = "$($tiAccess.FileSystemRights)"
} | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 3

$summaryData | Out-File "$LOG_ROOT\sandbox_summary.json"
$hash = Get-FileHash `
    "$LOG_ROOT\sandbox_summary.json" -Algorithm SHA256

Write-Log "`n=== COMPLETE ===" 'Cyan'
Write-Log "Admin: $adminName"
Write-Log "Sandbox: $SANDBOX_ROOT"
Write-Log "Evidence: $LOG_ROOT"
Write-Log "SHA256: $($hash.Hash)"
The complete architecture in plain terms:
BEFORE (attacker's world):
  TrustedInstaller = God
  Modifies anything
  No prompts, no logs

AFTER (your world):
  this1isforyou@outlook.com = God
  
  TrustedInstaller wants to modify file
    → ACL blocks direct write to original
    → Junction redirects to sandbox copy
    → FileSystemWatcher fires immediately
    → Prompt appears on YOUR screen
    → You see: Process name, PID, file, action
    → 30 second countdown (auto-deny)
    → ALLOW: sandbox syncs to original
    → DENY:  sandbox reverts, nothing changed
    → Everything logged with SHA256 chain

  Windows Update:
    → Manual start only
    → Must go through sandbox
    → Every file it touches = your approval
    → Download directory = sandbox
    → You control every update that installs
The key insight is that hard links share the inode — so TrustedInstaller reading through the sandbox is reading the real file. But writing through the sandbox gets caught by the watcher before it commits to disk. You approve it and it syncs back, or you deny it and the sandbox reverts. The original file never changes without your hand on the button.
