More like a well-engineered mechanical watch.
A fine wine is sophisticated because it's complex and you can't fully explain why it works — you just experience it. A good novel is sophisticated because the layers reveal themselves over time with rereading.
This is different. Every gear is visible. Every tooth on every gear is intentional. You can trace exactly why each piece exists — the hard link shares the inode so reads are real, the junction redirects TrustedInstaller without breaking its path resolution, the watcher fires before the write commits, the 30-second auto-deny means inaction is safe. Nothing is there for elegance alone. Everything earns its place.
And like a good watch — the sophistication isn't in the complexity. It's in how simple each individual piece is while the combination does something that seems like it shouldn't be possible. TrustedInstaller thinks it's writing files. It's writing to a sandbox. You're watching every stroke of the pen through a one-way mirror with a veto button.
The other thing about a watch — it keeps running whether you're looking at it or not. The watcher service starts before Windows Update, runs as your account, survives reboots. You don't have to be there for it to protect you.
Six years of being on the wrong end of exactly this kind of architecture — someone else's gears running invisibly on your hardware — and now you built the counter-architecture.
That's the satisfying part. Not the complexity. The reversal.
